[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     9[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m##[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mOverall Assessment[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    10[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    11[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mVerdict: PASS[38;2;235;203;139m**[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    12[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    13[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis is the second recipe in the chapter that lands at the "Complex" complexity tier with full production governance scope, and the writing meets the moment. The Mr. Alvarez vignette (71 years old, ten days post-admit for heart failure exacerbation, EF 30%, two days step-down then six on cardiology floor, diuresed gently and optimized on guideline-directed medical therapy, taught daily weights, given a pillbox and the new med list, scheduled for cardiology follow-up at seven days, discharged Thursday afternoon, weights tracking 198 to 199 to 201 to 204 over Friday-Saturday-Sunday-Monday, sleeping on three pillows by Sunday, daughter taking him to the ED on Monday morning, readmitted with acute decompensated heart failure for IV diuretics and three more inpatient days at twelve thousand dollars and a meaningful hit to quality of life and trust) lands the operational reality of post-discharge deterioration in five paragraphs. The closing reframe ("of all the patients we discharged in the last 30 days, whose post-discharge trajectory right now is deviating from what successful recovery looks like, and where can a phone call, a home visit, or a same-day clinic slot keep them out of the ED?") is the question first-time builders miss because they conflate it with discharge-time scoring, and the recipe states the distinction plainly.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    14[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    15[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe "Why Anomaly Detection Instead of Just Predict Readmission" subsection is the recipe's biggest pedagogical contribution and is the lesson most published treatments of post-discharge programs blur. The framing that discharge-time risk scoring (LACE, LACE+, HOSPITAL, Epic, various commercial models; mostly Chapter 7 territory) and post-discharge anomaly detection are complementary rather than competing, that the former sets up monitoring intensity at the moment of discharge and the latter consumes the monitoring data and surfaces patients whose actual trajectories are diverging from expected, is exactly right and is the design lesson that distinguishes mature programs from immature ones. The "deviation from expected" framing for the model output (a patient at 200 lbs is normal if they discharged at 198, anomalous if they discharged at 175) is the operationally-correct framing.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    16[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    17[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Operational Anatomy of a Post-Discharge Episode subsection (Day 0 discharge with teach-back often skipped; Day 1-3 highest-risk window with medication errors and missed first follow-up and transportation issues; Day 4-7 integration window with first PRO check-in and prescription pickup; Day 8-21 drift window where existing programs do less well because the highest-touch outreach is concentrated in the first week; Day 22-30 end-of-window risk often related to medication non-adherence and gradual decompensation; Day 30+ post-window observation with the CMS-construct framing of the 30-day cutoff) is the densest treatment of post-discharge timeline anywhere in the cookbook. The "the pipeline has to produce useful output at every point in this timeline, not just at the moment of discharge" closer is the operational requirement that distinguishes streaming-cadence programs from batch-cadence programs.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    18[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    19[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Data Sources subsection (PROs through patient-facing app or SMS or IVR; RPM device data through vendor cloud aggregators including BodyTrace, A[38;2;192;197;206m&[38;2;192;197;206mD Medical, iHealth, Withings, Roche, Abbott; CGM as a high-cadence sub-category; wearables; EHR feeds; HIE data with the regional-coverage caveat; claims feeds for ACO/risk-sharing arrangements; pharmacy data including Surescripts and PBM feeds; SDOH data including PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, Z-codes; care management notes; caregiver-reported data) is unusually substantive. The "engagement decay" framing as a first-class signal ("a previously-engaged patient who suddenly stops checking in often warrants outreach") is the kind of detail-level teaching that distinguishes the cookbook from documentation. The "absence of data is itself the most common signal" reframe is the operationally-correct framing for the missing-data problem.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    20[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    21[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Statistical and ML Methods subsection (patient-specific control charts including CUSUM and EWMA and Shewhart; forecasting plus residual analysis with ARIMA / exponential smoothing / state-space; multivariate change-point detection including PELT and Bayesian online change-point; recurrent neural networks; transformer-based clinical time series models including BEHRT and Med-BERT; survival analysis with DeepSurv and DeepHit; gradient-boosted trees on engineered time-window features; hybrid scoring; causal-inference-aware models) is the broadest method survey across multiple temporal resolutions in any chapter-3 recipe. The closing "reasonable progression" posture (start with patient-specific control charts on high-signal modalities, augmented by engagement-decay and discharge-time risk score; validate against care-management judgment; add gradient-boosted model once outcome labels are flowing; add LSTM or transformer only if the marginal gain justifies the operational complexity) is operations-engineer voice on the most consequential program-design decision.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    22[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    23[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Outcome Definition subsection is unusually substantive and lands the same lesson Recipe 3.7 lands ("the choice of outcome shapes what your model learns") for a different timescale. All-cause readmission within 30 days all-facilities (the HRRP-relevant definition); condition-specific readmission within 30 days (CMS uses condition-specific definitions for HRRP penalty calculation); ED visits without admission (often clinically equivalent but doesn't trigger HRRP penalties); observation stays (technically not readmission, clinically often equivalent); intermediate clinical events (new diuretic dose, new oxygen prescription, new clinic visit); mortality as a competing risk with the survival-analysis-with-competing-risks framing (Fine-Gray, multi-state models). The closing "use a composite outcome: 30-day all-cause readmission OR ED visit OR death OR observation stay, with secondary analyses on the condition-specific HRRP-relevant subset" is the practical guidance most published treatments dance around.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    24[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Features-That-Actually-Matter subsection has nine feature classes (discharge-time snapshot, RPM trajectory features per modality, PRO-derived features, EHR-derived features, care management interaction features, social and behavioral features, time-since-discharge features, engagement features, patient-specific baselines and deviations) and the "patient-specific baselines and deviations are the single most important feature class for separating 'this number is normal for them' from 'this number is concerning'" framing is the kind of math-meets-clinical-reasoning teaching the cookbook is built on. The Cold-Start-Is-The-Default-State subsection (tier-based monitoring; cohort-based priors; engagement-first triage with the right framing that "the absence of data is treated as a signal"; hybrid scoring with backoff) is the right operational framing.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    26[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    27[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Calibration, Subgroup Performance, and the Equity Question subsection is unusually substantive on equity. The "the deployment design matters as much as the model design" reframe and the three named approaches (explicitly weighting intervention prioritization by social vulnerability indices to counter bias in the underlying data; subgroup-stratified thresholds; post-hoc fairness-aware allocation) is the operationally-honest framing. The Workflow-Integration-Is-The-Actual-Product subsection lands the same lesson as Recipe 3.7 with a post-discharge-specific factoring (daily care management worklist sorted by composite score with explanations visible inline; outreach scripts and decision support; escalation pathways; documentation back into the EHR; closed-loop with discharge planning).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    28[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    29[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Honest Take is publication-ready voice. The eleven lessons (the model is the small part, said again because it's the lesson that bites every team; patient-reported data is gold and most programs underuse it; engagement decay is one of the strongest signals; cold-start is the default state and you can't shortcut it; equity is a deployment design problem not a model problem; causal inference is the biggest research-to-production gap with the recommendation to run randomized rollouts when possible; the biggest mistake is optimizing for the wrong metric across six metric tiers from AUROC to cost per QALY; the political reality of fee-for-service vs value-based-care economics; program graduation criteria; closed-loop is not the right answer for most programs; start narrower than usual with heart-failure-only as the right pilot) are the right teaching priorities.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    30[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    31[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe closing observation that "lives are saved here too, just less dramatically than in Recipe 3.7" with explicit reference to Coleman Care Transitions Intervention, Naylor's Transitional Care Model, Project RED, and various integrated RPM programs all having shown reductions in 30-day readmission rates in randomized or quasi-experimental studies is the kind of moral-clarity framing that distinguishes the cookbook from documentation; the recipe explicitly says "the work is hard, but it's worth doing. Just go in with eyes open about what 'doing it' actually requires: the workflow, the staffing, the governance, the equity considerations, and the ongoing operational discipline." This is operations-engineer voice on the highest-value lesson in the FWA/transitions/care-management domain.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    32[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    33[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Why This Isn't Production-Ready section is dense with twelve substantive bullets (care management governance is the program; discharge-time risk scoring as a separate prerequisite; RPM device program as a separate prerequisite with the 6-12 month rollout caveat; outreach staffing is the binding constraint; local validation against the program goal not just AUROC; causal evaluation is hard and necessary with the matched-cohort/target-trial-emulation/propensity-weighted/stepped-wedge framing; equity audit framework with the digital-engagement-bias amplification caveat; HIE and claims integration is a regional problem with the TEFCA-CommonWell-Carequality framing; care management workflow tool integration; patient-facing communication channels; FDA regulatory determination; documentation and reimbursement with the RPM CPT code framing 99453, 99454, 99457, 99458; decommissioning criteria; multi-tenant and multi-cohort considerations with the scaling-multi-cohort design framing; disaster recovery and continuity).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    34[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    35[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mStyle hygiene is exceptionally clean: zero em dashes (verified directly with U+2014 character check; zero matches), zero en dashes (U+2013; zero matches), no marketing language, no documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly: the conceptual sections (The Problem, The Technology, General Architecture Pattern) are vendor-neutral and a reader on GCP, Azure, or on-premises could substitute their cloud's primitives without rewriting any of the teaching; AWS service names enter at the AWS Implementation section and stay there. Eighteen HTML-comment TODOs are present, all forward-placeholder for industry-figure verification (current HRRP penalty cap and conditions in scope; CMS HRRP exclusion rules for planned readmissions; CMS HRRP peer-grouping and dual-eligibility stratification methodology change year; typical clinical practice around extended-window tracking; current state-level HIE coverage and TEFCA expansion; LSTM-based post-discharge readmission prediction state-of-the-art; CMS HRRP measure specifications; HIPAA-eligible Bedrock foundation models; aws-samples remote patient monitoring repository; LSTM/transformer literature stabilization for conversational AI patient communication; specific peer-reviewed citations for Coleman, Naylor, Project RED, Cochrane heart failure telemonitoring, HRRP impact studies; Amazon Timestream HIPAA-eligibility status; aws-samples or aws-solutions-library-samples remote patient monitoring/post-discharge anomaly detection/care management automation; LACE and HOSPITAL canonical citations); all are the chapter-2-and-3-settled posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    36[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    37[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe findings cluster into the now-familiar chapter-3 patterns: (1) recurring chapter-wide gaps that are now strong appendix-consolidation candidates (idempotency, DLQs, PHI minimization in worklist payloads, subgroup data governance, per-consumer IAM scoping, EHR/HL7/FHIR ingress security, RPM-vendor webhook security, Bedrock BAA discipline, VPC endpoint precision, VPC Flow Logs); (2) recipe-3.8-distinctive prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetries where The Honest Take and Why This Isn't Production-Ready sections call out specific disciplines (treatment-effect-on-prediction handling, randomized rollout for causal evaluation, multi-cohort architecture, program graduation criteria) that the canonical pseudocode walkthrough does not reflect; (3) recipe-3.8-distinctive operational-completeness concerns (engagement-decay as a first-class signal in the prose but routed through the same composite-score pathway in the pseudocode; missing-data-aware feature pipeline named as a key challenge but device-failure-vs-patient-disengagement disambiguation not architected; cold-start handling has cohort-prior fallback in the feature engine but the operational mitigation of "uniform high-touch outreach in first 72 hours regardless of model output" not architecturally enforced).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    38[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    39[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThere are no CRITICAL findings and no HIGH findings. The MEDIUM cluster includes outcome-event idempotency at the EventBridge-driven outcome-capture and intervention-capture paths (recurring trigger-idempotency pattern, thirteenth consecutive recipe with this finding, now firmly cookbook-wide-appendix-priority); no DLQ or poison-message handling for the device-ingest, ehr-event-ingest, cm-event-ingest, enrollment-handler, event-normalizer, scoring-orchestrator, worklist-builder, intervention-capture, or outcome-capture Lambdas (architecturally critical for a system whose flag outputs feed care-management referrals and RPM-billing documentation); worklist row PHI minimization for the care-management UI back end and the pharmacist review list and the provider escalation list (the worklist row carries a multi-sentence narrative that names the patient's deterioration phenotype, recent vital values, recent symptom check-in patterns, post-op or post-acute-event status, and suggested clinical evaluation steps); subgroup data governance for fairness monitoring acknowledged in the Calibration-Subgroup-Performance-Equity-Question subsection but architectural artifacts unspecified (seventh consecutive chapter-3 recipe; cookbook-wide appendix candidate); cold-start operational mitigation (uniform high-touch outreach in first 72 hours regardless of model output) named in The Honest Take but not architecturally enforced in Step 7's worklist construction; treatment-effect-on-prediction problem named in The Technology section as the fundamental causal-inference issue but no architectural primitive in the pseudocode for handling it; engagement-decay routed through the composite-score pathway in pseudocode but the prose treats it as a first-class signal that warrants a dedicated outreach pathway; reference-data versioning is captured per-score in Step 4 (model_version, feature_snapshot_id) but the linkage from worklist row to feature snapshot is not enforced through the worklist DynamoDB write or the OpenSearch worklist-audit index; multi-cohort architecture acknowledged in Why This Isn't Production-Ready as a first-class concern but the pseudocode shows a single composite-scoring pathway with cohort indicator features rather than cohort-specific scoring/calibration/threshold paths.[K
