[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     57[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mBAA posture is explicit: "Signed AWS BAA. All services configured per BAA requirements. RPM vendors and PRO vendors must have their own BAAs with the hospital" with a verified link to the [38;2;208;135;112m[[38;2;208;135;112mAWS HIPAA Eligible Services Reference[38;2;208;135;112m][38;2;208;135;112m([38;2;208;135;112mhttps://aws.amazon.com/compliance/hipaa-eligible-services-reference/[38;2;208;135;112m)[38;2;191;97;106m. The "RPM vendors and PRO vendors must have their own BAAs with the hospital" framing is an important addition for a recipe that depends substantially on third-party vendor data flows; this is the discipline that distinguishes mature deployments from immature ones.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     58[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Encryption coverage is complete across every PHI-bearing store: "Customer-managed KMS keys on every PHI-bearing store: Kinesis, DynamoDB, Timestream, S3, OpenSearch, SageMaker (volumes, Feature Store, model artifacts). TLS 1.2 or higher in transit. Webhook endpoints validate vendor signatures and reject unsigned traffic." The customer-managed-keys posture (rather than AWS-managed defaults) is the production-correct choice. The "webhook endpoints validate vendor signatures and reject unsigned traffic" framing is the right discipline for the RPM-vendor integration boundary that distinguishes this recipe from prior chapter-3 recipes.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     59[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m IAM is least-privilege with concrete examples in the Prerequisites table: "Device ingest Lambdas validate webhooks and write to the event stream. Feature engine reads from DynamoDB and Timestream, writes to Feature Store. Scoring orchestrator invokes the SageMaker endpoint, publishes to EventBridge. Worklist builder reads scores and writes worklist state. Care manager roles read worklist state and write intervention records only. Model team roles can train and deploy but cannot read PHI directly without explicit elevation. No [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140m*[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m permissions; every action scoped to specific resources." The "care manager roles ... write intervention records only" scoping is the right discipline for a workflow tool whose write surface is the intervention history.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     60[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m CloudTrail data events on every PHI-bearing store and on the worklist and audit indexes are required, with the explicit framing "Every score, every worklist generation, every intervention capture, every outcome event is logged. Log retention per organizational policy and applicable regulations." This is the audit-trail discipline a hospital regulatory affairs team can defend in front of a CMS surveyor or a clinical safety review and is also the discipline that supports RPM CPT code billing documentation.[K
