[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     93[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m "The Technology" Calibration-Subgroup-Performance-And-The-Equity-Question subsection ("Age band, sex, race and ethnicity (where structurally captured), insurance status, language, neighborhood SES, primary diagnosis, discharge disposition. Track AUROC, PRAUC, calibration ECE, alert rate, intervention rate, and (when measurable) the change in readmission rate per subgroup attributable to the program"); "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" Equity-Audit-Framework bullet ("Subgroup performance monitoring across age bands, sex, race and ethnicity (where structurally captured), language, insurance status, neighborhood-level SES (Area Deprivation Index, social vulnerability index), and dual-eligibility status").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     94[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe is unusually clear about subgroup dimensions and the equity stakes, naming the digital-engagement-bias amplification problem ("models trained on patient-reported data can encode digital-engagement bias in ways that map onto socioeconomic and demographic disparities. Subgroup performance audits are not optional"). The framing-level treatment is the strongest in any chapter-3 recipe and explicitly acknowledges the deployment-design dimension ("a program that surfaces predicted-higher-risk patients for more intervention can either reduce disparities (by directing resources to underserved patients) or amplify them (by directing resources to patients who are easier to engage). The deployment design matters as much as the model design").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     95[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     96[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding rather than aspirational are not specified: where the demographic and patient-attribute store lives, who has read access, how it joins to worklist rows and intervention records, what the audit trail for subgroup queries looks like, what IAM scope the QuickSight dashboard role and the retraining job role need on demographic data, and how the dashboard avoids exposing row-level demographic data to dashboard viewers.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     97[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     98[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe post-discharge-specific amplification: SDOH data and digital engagement data and area-level proxies (Area Deprivation Index, social vulnerability index) are named as features and as monitoring dimensions. SDOH data is governed differently from clinical PHI in some regulatory regimes (state laws often restrict secondary use of demographic data more tightly than HIPAA restricts PHI; the same applies to SDOH attributes captured through PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, and Z-codes). The framing-level treatment is correct; the architectural backstop that operationalizes it is missing. Same finding shape as Recipes 3.2 S2, 3.3 S2, 3.4 S2, 3.5 S2, 3.6 S3, 3.7 S2 (now seven chapter-3 recipes deep).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     99[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add a "Subgroup data access" paragraph or row to Prerequisites: "Subgroup performance and intervention-allocation monitoring requires read access to patient demographic attributes (age band, sex, race, ethnicity, preferred language, insurance type, dual-eligibility status), area-level attributes (Area Deprivation Index, social vulnerability index, neighborhood SES), and SDOH attributes (housing stability, food security, transportation, social support, language proficiency) captured through PRAPARE / AHC HRSN / Z-codes. These attributes may be governed differently from clinical PHI in some regulatory regimes (state laws often restrict secondary use of race and ethnicity data and SDOH data); restrict read access to the demographic-and-attribute store to the retraining job role and the fairness-monitoring dashboard role, and audit subgroup queries via CloudTrail data events. The QuickSight dashboard backed by Athena should query an aggregated subgroup-metrics table (alert rate by age band by neighborhood-SES quartile, calibration ECE by sex, intervention rate by language, change in 30-day readmission rate per subgroup attributable to the program), not the raw demographic-joined worklist archive, so that dashboard-user access does not require row-level read on the subgroup attributes."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    100[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    101[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mStrengthen the IAM row with the per-role scope: retraining job role gets [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mglue:GetTable[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140ms3:GetObject[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m only on the demographic-joined view; fairness-monitoring dashboard role gets read-only on the aggregated subgroup-metrics table. With this finding now flagged across seven chapter-3 recipes, the subgroup-governance appendix is the second-highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment alongside trigger-idempotency.[K
