[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    118[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe correctly identifies webhook signature verification as the right discipline ("verify the vendor's signature. Reject anything that doesn't validate") and the encryption row carries the framing "Webhook endpoints validate vendor signatures and reject unsigned traffic." But the specifics of the verification protocol are not specified: HMAC-SHA256 is the most common scheme (BodyTrace, Withings, iHealth, A[38;2;191;97;106m&[38;2;191;97;106mD Medical use variants), but some vendors use mutual TLS (mTLS) with API Gateway custom domain authorizers, some use OAuth 2.0 client credentials flows with bearer-token validation, some use IP allowlisting plus shared-secret HMAC, and some use vendor-specific JWT validation against a vendor JWKS endpoint.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    119[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    120[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mEach vendor's protocol has different operational implications: HMAC-SHA256 requires per-vendor signing-secret rotation; mTLS requires per-vendor client-certificate management; OAuth 2.0 requires token introspection or local JWT validation against a vendor JWKS that must be cached and rotated. The recipe's framing-level treatment is correct; the architectural backstop (per-vendor signature scheme, secret rotation cadence, replay-attack protection via timestamp validation, IP allowlisting where supported) is missing.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    121[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    122[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mFor a recipe that depends on multiple RPM-vendor integrations (BodyTrace, A[38;2;191;97;106m&[38;2;191;97;106mD Medical, iHealth, Withings, Roche, Abbott named in the Data Sources section), the per-vendor variation is the operational reality. Same finding shape as the EHR-ingress security pattern in prior recipes (Recipes 3.4 S3, 3.5 S4, 3.6 S6, 3.7 S4).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    123[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add an RPM-webhook-security paragraph to the API Gateway + Lambda paragraph: "RPM device vendor webhook integrations have per-vendor signature schemes. The most common is HMAC-SHA256 with a vendor-specific signing secret, replay-attack protection via timestamp validation (reject webhooks whose timestamp is more than a configurable window old), and per-vendor IP allowlisting at the API Gateway resource policy where the vendor publishes its source-IP range. Some vendors use mutual TLS (mTLS) with API Gateway custom domain authorizers; some use OAuth 2.0 client credentials with bearer-token validation against a vendor JWKS endpoint. Per-vendor signing secrets are rotated per the vendor's recommended cadence (typically 90-day rotation) and stored in AWS Secrets Manager with rotation Lambdas where supported. The device-ingest Lambda's IAM role grants [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140msecretsmanager:GetSecretValue[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m on the per-vendor signing secret only; the Lambda fetches the secret at cold start and caches it through the warm-instance lifetime with a forced refresh on signature-validation failure (handles the rotation window). CloudTrail data events on the secret-fetch operation provide the audit trail."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    124[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
