[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    452[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m###[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mVoice Reviewer[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    453[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    454[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m####[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mWhat's Done Well[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    455[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    456[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe opening Mr. Alvarez vignette is publication-ready voice. The 71-year-old, the heart-failure exacerbation with EF 30%, the two days in step-down then six on cardiology floor, the diuresis and GDMT optimization, the daily-weights teaching with the pillbox and the new med list, the seven-day cardiology follow-up, the Thursday-afternoon discharge, the chicken-and-rice dinner from his daughter, the weights tracking 198 to 199 to 201 to 204 over Friday-Saturday-Sunday-Monday, the puffier ankles he doesn't mention because nobody asked about ankles, the two pillows turning into three pillows, the daughter taking him to the ED Monday morning, the readmission for IV diuretics and three more inpatient days at twelve thousand dollars and a meaningful hit to quality of life and trust, and the data trail showing weights went up from 198 to 199 to 201 to 204 in four days, which is the textbook "call your doctor" trigger from heart failure self-management materials, that he logged every weight on the patient portal, that the portal stored them, that nobody acted on them, that the cardiologist's office had thirty new patient messages that morning, that the hospital's care management team was understaffed and prioritizing day-1-and-day-2 patients not day-three-and-day-four post-discharge: this is the densest post-discharge-deterioration framing in any cookbook recipe and is the closest the cookbook has come to a real-world clinical narrative. The closing reframe ("Not the well-studied 'score this patient at discharge for likelihood of 30-day readmission' problem ... The harder, more operational question is: of all the patients we discharged in the last 30 days, whose post-discharge trajectory right now is deviating from what successful recovery looks like, and where can a phone call, a home visit, or a same-day clinic slot keep them out of the ED?") is the system reframe most first-time builders miss and the recipe states it plainly.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    457[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    458[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe seven-paragraph "the reason this problem lands at the complex end of the chapter, despite years of academic work on readmission prediction" subsection (the signal is diffuse and slow; baselines are deeply personal and the post-discharge baseline isn't the inpatient baseline; intervention capacity is the binding constraint; causality and correlation are tangled; the outcome label is operationally messy; patient-reported data is messy and sparse and biased; workflow integration is, again, the actual product; equity is a first-order concern, not a side note) is the right pedagogical scoping. Each paragraph ties to a specific post-discharge-domain concern that distinguishes the problem from inpatient deterioration (Recipe 3.7) and from one-shot discharge-time scoring (Chapter 7). The "missing data is itself the most common signal" reframe is the operationally-correct framing that distinguishes streaming-aware systems from snapshot-only systems.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    459[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    460[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe "Why 'Anomaly Detection' Instead of 'Just Predict Readmission'" subsection is the recipe's biggest pedagogical contribution and is the design distinction most published treatments blur. The framing that discharge-time risk scoring (LACE, LACE+, HOSPITAL, Epic, commercial models; Chapter 7 territory) and post-discharge anomaly detection are complementary and answer different questions, and that the framing as anomaly detection is deliberate because the question is fundamentally "deviation from expected" rather than "absolute level of risk," is exactly the lesson first-time builders need. The "a patient discharged at 198 lbs whose weight is 200 on day three is normal. The same patient at 204 on day three is anomalous. The signal isn't the weight. It's the deviation from the expected weight trajectory for this patient given their condition, their discharge status, and their personal baseline" framing lands the reframe in three sentences.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    461[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    462[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Operational Anatomy of a Post-Discharge Episode subsection (Day 0 through Day 30+) is the densest treatment of post-discharge timeline in any cookbook recipe. Each window's clinical and operational reality is named: Day 0 with teach-back often skipped, Day 1-3 as the highest-risk window with medication errors and missed first follow-up, Day 4-7 as the integration window, Day 8-21 as the drift window where existing programs do less well, Day 22-30 as the end-of-window risk for late-cluster readmissions, Day 30+ as the post-window observation with the CMS-construct framing. The "the highest-touch outreach is concentrated in the first week" framing for the drift window is a specific operational reality that distinguishes well-designed programs from ones that mirror the discharge-week intensity.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    463[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    464[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Data Sources subsection (PROs, RPM device data, CGM, wearables, EHR feeds, HIE data, claims feed, pharmacy data, SDOH data, care management notes, caregiver-reported data) is comprehensive and the per-source operational caveats are specific. Naming representative vendors (BodyTrace, A[38;2;191;97;106m&[38;2;191;97;106mD Medical, iHealth, Withings, Roche, Abbott; CipherHealth, GetWellNetwork, Memora Health; PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, Z-codes; Salesforce Health Cloud, Epic Healthy Planet, Cerner HealtheRegistries, Innovaccer, Lumeris, ZeOmega Jiva, Lightbeam) gives the reader the integration landscape rather than abstract framing.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    465[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    466[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Statistical and ML Methods subsection (patient-specific control charts including CUSUM and EWMA and Shewhart; forecasting plus residual analysis; multivariate change-point detection; recurrent neural networks; transformer-based clinical time series models with explicit reference to BEHRT and Med-BERT; survival analysis with DeepSurv and DeepHit; gradient-boosted trees on engineered time-window features; hybrid scoring; causal-inference-aware models) is the broadest method survey across multiple temporal resolutions in any chapter-3 recipe. The closing "reasonable progression" posture is operations-engineer voice on the most consequential program-design decision.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    467[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    468[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Outcome Definition subsection lands the same lesson Recipe 3.7 lands ("the choice of outcome shapes what your model learns") for a different timescale with the post-discharge-specific operational realities (HRRP-relevant all-cause-30-day-all-facilities, condition-specific, ED visits without admission, observation stays, intermediate clinical events, mortality as a competing risk). The "use a composite outcome: 30-day all-cause readmission OR ED visit OR death OR observation stay, with secondary analyses on the condition-specific HRRP-relevant subset" closing is the practical guidance most published treatments dance around.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    469[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    470[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Cold-Start-Is-the-Default-State subsection is the right operational framing. Engagement-first triage as a cold-start mitigation ("a patient who hasn't logged a single weight by day 3 is escalated to the care management team for outreach, regardless of any other signal") is a specific mechanism that distinguishes well-designed programs from ones that defer to model output during the cold-start window.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    471[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    472[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Calibration, Subgroup Performance, and the Equity Question subsection is unusually substantive on equity. The "the deployment design matters as much as the model design" reframe and the three named approaches (explicitly weighting intervention prioritization by social vulnerability indices to counter bias in the underlying data; subgroup-stratified thresholds; post-hoc fairness-aware allocation) is the operationally-honest framing that distinguishes equity-aware programs from programs that monitor subgroup performance but don't act on it.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    473[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    474[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Honest Take is publication-ready voice. The eleven lessons are the right teaching priorities. The "patient-reported data is gold and most programs underuse it" lesson is unusually specific (the data is higher-signal than RPM device data because patients know how they're feeling and will tell you if you ask; the trick is making the asking low-friction and timing the asks well). The "engagement decay is one of the strongest signals" lesson with the three-cause taxonomy (about half are getting better and not bothering anymore; some meaningful fraction are getting worse and not feeling up to engagement; some have a logistical problem) plus the "we noticed you stopped checking in; everything okay?" script is operations-engineer voice on the highest-yield outreach pattern. The "cold-start is the default state and you can't shortcut it" lesson with the explicit "the right response is uniform high-touch outreach in the first 72 hours regardless of model output" framing is the operational discipline most first-time builders need to hear. The "equity is a deployment design problem, not a model problem" lesson with the three deployment patterns (explicit weighting toward higher-vulnerability populations, parallel non-digital monitoring tracks, proactive device and language provision) is the equity-aware-deployment teaching most published treatments skip. The "biggest mistake I see: optimizing for the wrong metric" lesson with the six metric tiers (AUROC, top-decile capture, successful contact rate, intervention rate, reduced-readmission-rate-vs-matched-controls, cost-per-readmission-avoided) is the kind of math-meets-operations framing the cookbook is built on.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    475[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    476[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe closing "lives are saved here too, just less dramatically than in Recipe 3.7" framing with explicit reference to Coleman Care Transitions Intervention, Naylor's Transitional Care Model, Project RED, and various integrated RPM programs is the kind of moral-clarity framing that distinguishes the cookbook from documentation. The "the work is hard, but it's worth doing" closing is the right posture for a complex-tier production-grade program.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    477[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    478[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Variations and Extensions section covers eleven adjacent patterns at substantive depth. The closed-loop framing is appropriately cautious ("usually worth doing only in mature programs with strong governance"); the patient-facing transparency framing acknowledges the tradeoffs honestly ("patients who see 'high risk' labels can become anxious in counterproductive ways, and the disclosure raises informed-consent considerations"); the conversational AI patient check-ins variation correctly identifies the emerging-but-rare deployment status.[K
